message: Members of the Senate were officially sworn in today. Looking forward to continuing our work on behalf of the American people with a Republican majority.

Obamacare is one of the largest, most colossal cases of consumer fraud perpetrated in the United States. Yesterday a resolution was introduced in the Senate to begin the process of repealing this failed health care law.

Less than a year ago, Democrats called for a nine-person Supreme Court. We made it clear that the American people deserved a voice in who chooses the next Supreme Court Justice. The people have spoken, and Democrats have responded by threatening to block Supreme Court nominations indefinitely. What happened to #WeNeedNine?

We can do a lot better than Obamacare, and that’s what we intend to do—repeal Obamacare to give Americans more options for health care at a price people can afford. And don’t believe the propaganda: there will be an orderly, careful transition to ensure that no one falls through the cracks during this process.

Today the House and Senate met for a joint session of Congress to tally the votes of the Electoral College. Mr. Trump was certified President-elect of the United States, and Mr. Pence was certified Vice President-elect of the United States. Here’s a video of the Senate pages carrying the ballot boxes through the Capitol rotunda to the House chamber.

Thankful today and every day for our law enforcement #heroesinblue. I look forward to continuing to work with the law enforcement community, and hope you’ll join me in thanking these brave individuals today for Law Enforcement Appreciation Day.

Senator Jeff Sessions has a good record prosecuting the Ku Klux Klan, voting for the Voting Rights Act, and prosecuting voter fraud when minority communities have been denied their right to vote. And I think as Attorney General, he’ll be able to tell President Trump no when he has to, based on the law of the land. Democrats have said they want to slow down President-elect Trump’s cabinet nominees, and I believe a lot of this is posturing for show.

Early this morning I voted for the Obamacare repeal resolution. This will give Congress the tools it needs to repeal this failing health care law. I am committed to a careful, orderly transition to health care solutions that work.

Today at a Senate Intel Committee confirmation hearing, I questioned President-elect Trump’s nominee to be CIA Director, Congressman Mike Pompeo. Our intelligence gathering capabilities are critical. The brave people who conduct these activities should not have to restrain their lawful activities for fear of political retribution.

The world witnessed a peaceful transition of power today-a hallmark of our democracy. The Senate took critical next steps by confirming two of President Trump's cabinet nominees, Jim Mattis as Secretary of Defense and John Kelly as Secretary of Homeland Security. I met with both of these men recently and am confident in their ability to lead. Unfortunately, Senate Democrats continue to obstruct other well-qualified, non-controversial cabinet nominees in a spiteful attempt to deny the President his team. It's particularly alarming that Democrats are holding up a vote on the nominee to be CIA Director. The election is over, and it's time for Democrats to drop this divisive strategy for the good of the country.

For years, the previous Administration inexplicably robbed this country of tens of thousands of new jobs and a chance to become less dependent on unstable sources of energy. Today’s decision by President Trump will boost the economy, strengthen national security, and help Texans and all Americans have more access to affordable energy.

Legislation update: I’ve signed on to cosponsor the Death Tax Repeal Act of 2017 to permanently repeal the federal estate tax. Punishing families for the death of a loved one with a burdensome tax suffocates the finances of ranches and small businesses across Texas and America. Repealing the death tax is another step toward reducing unnecessary taxation and regulation to strengthen our economy.

Legislation update: This week I introduced the Iran Non-nuclear Sanctions Act with Senator Marco Rubio and Senator Todd Young. Iran remains the world’s foremost state sponsor of terror and the biggest destabilizing force in the Middle East. It’s time to impose real economic consequences for Iran’s actions to make clear that we oppose Iran’s human rights abuses, terrorist activities around the world, and pursuit of ballistic missile capabilities.   The Iran Non-nuclear Sanctions Act, among other things, would impose sanctions against Iran’s Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) and Mahan Air, an Iranian airline that has helped the IRCG to spread terrorism and militancy; expand current sanctions and impose new sanctions against Iran for its egregious human rights abuses, while also mandated full transparency to Congress on all American citizens detained or kidnapped by Iran; impose sanctions on persons involved in sectors of Iran’s economy that support, directly or indirectly, Iran’s ballistic program; and codify current prohibitions against Iran’s direct and indirect access to the U.S. financial system.

Every year, hundreds of thousands of folks descend on Washington and gather around the country to march for the rights of the unborn. Today, I stand with you in solidarity and will continue the fight for life.

Regarding the President’s recent executive order on immigration: public safety is the number one responsibility of the federal government. I support the vetting of refugees and immigrants coming into our country, but I oppose blanket exclusion of anybody according to their religion. That’s not what America is all about.
I wanted to share with you some of the highlights of the first few weeks of this Congress. We’re ready to get to work.
Judge Gorsuch is an excellent choice to serve as our next Supreme Court Justice. I look forward to supporting his nomination.

Today, I voted to move forward the nomination of Jeff Sessions to be the next Attorney General. I’ve had the honor of serving alongside Senator Sessions on the Judiciary Committee since I was first elected to the Senate. Senator Sessions has devoted his life to public service, and his qualifications cannot be questioned. He has a history of protecting and defending the Constitution and the rule of law for all people. Senator Sessions is the right choice to serve as our nation’s top law enforcement officer, and I look forward to confirming him as Attorney General soon.

Today I voted to confirm Rex Tillerson as Secretary of State. I believe him to be a person of conviction, competence, and character. Rex believes in putting this country first, and I have no doubt that he’ll serve the American people with great integrity and care.

I was able to spend some time with Judge Gorsuch today. His resume, background, and impartiality in applying the text of the Constitution are universally respected. I believe him to be eminently well-qualified to serve on the Supreme Court and look forward to his confirmation.

Like many great Texas heroes, the first African-American to earn the Navy Cross started from humble beginnings. Doris “Dorie” Miller failed eighth grade twice and was deemed unsuitable for a Depression-era government assistance job by the age of 19. This didn’t stop him from fighting his way into a job on the USS West Virginia. During the attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941, he heard a roar as Japanese bombs hit his ship. He had no experience with anti-aircraft weapons, but Dorie didn’t hesitate when he spotted an unmanned machine gun station and took aim at the incoming Japanese bombers.   Men who served alongside him that day recall Dorie shooting down as many as six Japanese bombers, although the true number has never been known. Sadly, Dorie’s heroic service in defense of his country came to an end two years later when a Japanese torpedo dealt a fatal blow to the USS Liscome Bay. As we know, Dorie’s story is just one of the many incredible biographies that started here in Texas. I’m proud to honor his  legacy in celebration of #BlackHistoryMonth.

This week, I’ll be voting to confirm Betsy DeVos as Secretary of Education. Power over education should be handed back down to the states, so that parents and teachers can choose how best to accomplish our universal goal of making sure every child has a good education. Ms. DeVos will lead this effort, so that parents, teachers and our local school districts will have a greater role in these important decisions.

Sam McCulloch was a free man and a private in the Matagorda Volunteer Company during the Texas Revolution. The first soldier to attack the Mexican army garrison at Goliad, Sam was hit in the shoulder by a musket ball, marking another first—the first person wounded in our Republic’s fight for independence.  McCulloch didn’t let injury didn’t stop him. He went on to fight in the battle of Plum Creek and became a spy for the Republic of Texas Army when San Antonio was invaded in 1842. He passed away about 50 years later, leaving behind a legacy of bravery and commitment to his beloved Texas.  Private McCulloch is seen below in The Battle of Goliad painting by Kermit Oliver, part of the University of Texas at San Antonio special collections. #BlackHistoryMonth

Bessie Coleman didn’t let anyone ground her from her dream of flying. She was born in Atlanta, Texas in 1892. At a time when very few women or African-Americans could be pilots, she was determined. After being denied from every flight school she approached, Bessie learned French, saved her money, and moved to Paris to pursue her dream of flight. After receiving an international pilot’s license, she returned to the United States to perform aerial stunts as the first female African-American pilot.    Bessie used this new position of influence to encourage women to pursue careers in aviation, and as a platform to fight for equality—refusing to perform anywhere that would not admit African-Americans. Bessie’s career inspired countless women after her to take to the skies, and her commitment to equality continues to inspire us today.

Happy Independence Day, Texans! An excerpt from the Unanimous Declaration of Independence made by the Delegates of the People of Texas in General Convention at the Town of Washington:   When a government has ceased to protect the lives, liberty and property of the people, from whom its legitimate powers are derived, and for the advancement of whose happiness it was instituted, and so far from being a guarantee for the enjoyment of those inestimable and inalienable rights, becomes an instrument in the hands of evil rulers for their oppression.   When the Federal Republican Constitution of their country, which they have sworn to support, no longer has a substantial existence, and the whole nature of their government has been forcibly changed, without their consent, from a restricted federative republic, composed of sovereign states, to a consolidated central military despotism, in which every interest is disregarded but that of the army and the priesthood, both the eternal enemies of civil liberty, the everready minions of power, and the usual instruments of tyrants.   When, long after the spirit of the constitution has departed, moderation is at length so far lost by those in power, that even the semblance of freedom is removed, and the forms themselves of the constitution discontinued, and so far from their petitions and remonstrances being regarded, the agents who bear them are thrown into dungeons, and mercenary armies sent forth to force a new government upon them at the point of the bayonet.   When, in consequence of such acts of malfeasance and abdication on the part of the government, anarchy prevails, and civil society is dissolved into its original elements. In such a crisis, the first law of nature, the right of self-preservation, the inherent and inalienable rights of the people to appeal to first principles, and take their political affairs into their own hands in extreme cases, enjoins it as a right towards themselves, and a sacred obligation to their posterity, to abolish such government, and create another in its stead, calculated to rescue them from impending dangers, and to secure their future welfare and happiness.   Nations, as well as individuals, are amenable for their acts to the public opinion of mankind. A statement of a part of our grievances is therefore submitted to an impartial world, in justification of the hazardous but unavoidable step now taken, of severing our political connection with the Mexican people, and assuming an independent attitude among the nations of the earth.   --   We, therefore, the delegates with plenary powers of the people of Texas, in solemn convention assembled, appealing to a candid world for the necessities of our condition, do hereby resolve and declare, that our political connection with the Mexican nation has forever ended, and that the people of Texas do now constitute a free, Sovereign, and independent republic, and are fully invested with all the rights and attributes which properly belong to independent nations; and, conscious of the rectitude of our intentions, we fearlessly and confidently commit the issue to the decision of the Supreme arbiter of the destinies of nations.

This week is not just about moving past the failures of Obamacare, but also laying the groundwork for providing access to better care and eliminating big government burdens that are hurting Americans. The individual mandate is a prime example of government getting in the way of individual freedom and the right to choose. We really should call it the penalty that government imposes on its citizens for failing to purchase a product they don’t want and in some cases don’t even need. Millions of Americans are penalized every year by their own government and forced to pay a fine that could be used on coverage that might actually suit their needs. So tonight we’ll be working on a possible solution and way forward, something I call the ‘Freedom to Choose’ plan, to eliminate this destructive mandate.

“Judges cannot—nor should they try to—align our legal system with the Church’s moral teaching whenever the two diverge.” Professor Barrett, who has been nominated to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit, believes that judges must uphold the rule of law even when it conflicts with what a judge thinks it should say. This weekend’s news from Sutherland Springs was truly heartbreaking. The First Baptist congregation, first responders, and Sutherland Springs community continue to be in my prayers.  As new details emerge from the ongoing investigation, we need to ask ourselves how this happened and what could’ve been done to prevent it. We know, for example, that the gunman was court martialed by the Air Force and convicted of serious domestic abuse.   This critically important information from the suspect’s criminal history was not uploaded into the relevant background check databases, even though federal law clearly requires that this be done. The Air Force has admitted that the gunman’s conviction should’ve barred him from ever possessing firearms. But because there was no record of his conviction, he was able to lie his way into acquiring them.  According to the FBI, the number of relevant records that are uploaded to the national database is staggeringly low. This is unacceptable and must change. I plan to introduce legislation to ensure that all federal departments and agencies, including the Department of Defense, upload the required conviction records into the national database.

One in twelve veterans across the country call the state of Texas home. I hope you’ll join me today in expressing gratitude to all of those who have served our great nation. To our veterans: my humblest thanks.

For years, federal agencies and states have failed to upload criminal records to the national instant criminal background check system (NICS) without consequence. I introduced the Fix NICS Act with bipartisan support this week to fix this systemic problem by requiring federal agencies and states to produce NICS implementation plans focused on uploading all information to the background check system showing that a person is prohibited from purchasing or possessing firearms under current law. It will also hold federal agencies that fail to upload relevant records accountable and reward states who comply with their NICS implementation plans through federal grant preferences and incentives. Fix NICS will also increase accountability through public reporting for states who do not comply with implementation plans.   We must all do our part to prevent another disaster like Sutherland Springs from happening again. Thanks to Senators Scott, Hatch, and Heller for the support. The Fix NICS Act is also supported by the NRA, the National Shooting Sports Foundation, and the Fraternal Order of Police.

Simplifying our nation’s tax code is the jumpstart our economy needs to bring jobs back and leave more money in the pockets of hardworking Texans. This is a big moment for American families and small businesses who are ready to turn the page on an Obama-era recovery that has been far too sluggish.   A family of four in Texas making the median income will see their taxes cut by thousands of dollars - money they can save or spend on what they want instead of handing it over to Washington. And for Texas small businesses this bill means less time trying to navigate the code and more time creating jobs.   There’s still work to be done, but I’m grateful for the unified effort to get this over the goal line in the Senate. I look forward to getting tax reform to the President’s desk and deliver on promise of pro-growth tax reform for the American people.
